# Markdown General Standards

## üìù **Markdown Formatting Rules**

### **File Structure**

- Use descriptive filenames with clear purpose
- Include creation dates when relevant (YYYY-MM-DD format)
- Use kebab-case for multi-word filenames
- Maintain consistent directory structure

### **Header Hierarchy**

- Start with `#` for main title
- Use `##` for major sections
- Use `###` for subsections
- Avoid skipping header levels (no jumping from `#` to `###`)
- Keep headers descriptive but concise

### **Content Organization**

- Use bullet points for lists
- Use numbered lists for sequential steps
- Include code blocks for technical content
- Use tables for structured data
- Add alt text for images

### **Code Blocks**

- Specify language for syntax highlighting
- Use fenced code blocks (```)
- Include comments in longer code examples
- Test code examples to ensure they work

### **Links and References**

- Use descriptive link text
- Verify all links work
- Use relative links within the project
- Include anchor links for long documents

## üìã **Quality Assurance**

### **Pre-Commit Checks**

- **No HTML tags** in markdown content (except valid HTML elements)
- **Proper markdown syntax** throughout all files
- **Consistent formatting** across all pages
- **Working navigation** on all rendered pages

### **Validation Commands**

```bash
# Check for common markdown issues
grep -r "<[^/]" docs/ --include="*.md"
grep -r "http://" docs/ --include="*.md"
```
